   <mods:abstract>Believes that the fate of the Marquis de Lafayette depends entirely on the
            United States. Madame de Maisonneuve, sister of Mr. de Maubourg just arrived in Olmutz
            with the news that Mr. de Lafayette has friends in the Netherlands who make his case
            directly to the Emperor and she is almost positive that that will procure his liberty.
            The United States aided Lafayette in his prison in Madgebourg and does the same in
            Olmutz. He wishes for news of his family and articles every week. Hopes for him to
            receive more humane treatment, such as fresh air and exercise two hours a day and access
            to newspapers and books. Letter of the wife of the Commander of Neisse, the last
            Prussian prison where Lafayette was kept, shown to the ambassador, who believes that a
            formal request by the United States would give him his liberty. Has to wait for the
            ambassador to communicate this information to General Washington. In
            French.</mods:abstract>
